title: The Lost Temple of Baal-Shamin At Palmyra, Syria

description.text:
The ancient city of Palmyra is one of the most beautiful, historical, and archaeologically significant sites on the planet (no seriously, even the history of its excavation is absolutely awesome). And it's being destroyed right now by the forces of the Islamic State that are currently occupying the region.

Despite promises to the contrary, ISIS has begun randomly blowing up the world's heritage as they continue their reign of terror in the Middle East.

This week all of us lost the Temple of Ba'al-shamin, one of the city's most sacred sites to a variant of the region's most important ancient god.
http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/24/world/middleeast/islamic-state-blows-up-ancient-temple-at-syrias-palmyra-ruins.html?smid=fb-share&_r=1

The real version is gone forever—Sadly, before laser scanners could get to it (as far as I know?) to preserve a millimeter accurate digital representation of the temple. Photographs however, can serve in a pinch. And using a combination of structure from motion and straight up modelling, I built a slapdash version of this historical wonder today, so that some version of it can live on in 3D.

For more on digital heritage, art, archaeology, and everything in between, check out Open Access Antiquarianism. http://openaccessantiquarianism.com/

comments.text:
If we did not have people in the world arming terrorists such as those, we would not have lost this or any of the great libraries of the past.
There are from what I understand a few libraries left in Iran, but there are people in this world that want that country to turn into another Libya, Iraq, Egypt, and Syria. All countries that lost many great artifacts in the past few years.
Also just think how many other galaxy's we could have visited by now if we had not destroyed all the modern technology time and time again, and we are now at another peak and can see the coming end now in many parts of the world.
I think that it is great that we can do 3D creations from photos, but the world has many statues and many other things that are no longer usable, just like the mechanical computer found off Greece nearly 100 years ago and it is so fragile that the CT machine to find out just how complex was sent from England so that it could be scanned. It is amazing the number of specialized gears, cams, and eccentrics. Just so someone could know the phase of the moon, positions of the planets, eclipses, and seasons. All designed about 60 BCE by some unknown to us now engineers and scientists.
I think it would be interesting to say the least to make a working copy of that computer on a 3D printer, but from what I understand someone already has done this on a computer simulation, so we are already part way there.

description.text:
A replacement scale (plasticky bit) for a 58mm Victorinox Classic Swiss Army Knife.

There are two versions - one is solid, and the other has a void in it for an ultra-thin Verbatim flash drive. Neither has a toothpick holder, because seriously, who uses the toothpick on their pocket knife? If you feel the ned to add one, you can edit the design on Tinkercad.

I wrote a blog post about making these here, if you're interested.

Tinkercad - Solid / USB

Download and print. Designed specifically to work well on a MakerBot 2X, but honestly should work fine anywhere.

I have never tried the solid version. Chances are it could be made a little thinner, if it's too chunky for you.

Depending on the precision of your printer, you may also need to widen the rivet holes a little to get it to snap on nicely.

The Garmin Zümo 220 is a waterproof motorbike navigation system, but how "waterproof" is that? On August 17th, while riding in Germany, the poor Zümo got so much water thrown at it, that it's mini-USB connector got wet... Which then resulted in malfunctioning due to the short-cut on the connector.

In defense of the Zümo... the weather was utterly horrible. All day. :-)

Anyway, riding without navigation in the rain isn't my thing... So, I figured to have a go at constructing a rain cover - one would only need this in heavy rain, though. But as that tends to find me, here's my first try to construct this.

It's just a loose cover, for now & I have the idea that it might have come out a little tight at the top-end - around the lock switch? I'll need to look into that. It does fit, though - good enough to see if the concept works.

I've also printed an fastener point, so I could use a rubber band to allow for a quick mount, while on a trip. Might be better to bolt that on, but I've super-glued it for now.

Very much a "Work-in-progress", though.

I haven't got the 2 lofts in the design quite right as yet: as the body angles on the side & the top of the Zumo are different (50° & 30°) it's a bit of a trick to get those properly aligned.

There also seems to be another error in the design, as merging the 3 body components into 1 single body is giving an error. The error was removed using 3D Builder (stored in the "cured" file). Another thing too look in to, I guess.

All in good time. First, I'll see if this would help keeping the water away from the mini USB... :-)

3D printed the cover & anchor seperately, then glued those together. Mount on the Zumo with a rubber band.
20% fill on both, no special requirements - yet. :-)

description.text:
JUST GIVE HIM FIVE AND HE WILL SHINE!

This is a simple desk/bedside lamp. It's called Pepet (a typical Spanish name).

In order to make it work, you'll need some electronic parts, but don't worry, it's not difficult.
There are some hollow parts in the model so the cables can go through.
You can see it in action at http://youtu.be/1RRmRWKHw6I

DISCLAIMER: This is a DIY thing, do it at your own risk. I take no responsibility of its use or any damage that could cause.

See instructions...

Parts list:

  • 2 x 3w led module for arduino.
  • 1 x touch sensor module for arduino (mine is from sainsmart).
  • 1 x USB to 2.1mm barrel plug cable (or arduino 5v power supply with 2.1mm socket)
  • 1 x DC power jack 2.1mm panel mount socket
  • 4 x small self tapping screws (to hold the leds)
  • female to female dupont "y" cables (if you don't find "y" cables, you have to customize them because you need to connect one cable to two leds, so you'll need a "y". Check the pictures for further instructions. I suggest you make your own dupont cables.

Printing settings:

  • Printed without supports
  • 10-20% infill
  • 0.25/0.3 layer (to save time)
  • print speed about 50-60mm/s
  • 3 outer shells

Note: As you can see in the pictures the hand is a bit ugly. This is because it was the first time I printed it and speed was to high. I recommend you slow down the printing speed when printer starts with the hand.

Hope you like it!!
If you print it, please post some pictures!!

description.text:
I own two of these printers and their located in my bedroom. And most of my prints are greater than 3 or 4 hours and happen at night. The way they are situated on a desk at the foot of my bed, the fans on the two can be quite loud being that they are facing right at me. So I had seen on here that someone else had did the same thing, but for another type of power supply. So here is is based on sound canceling technology. As you can see in the photos I used a type of foam to help absorb some sound on the way out you can use something similar, fiberglass works well also. I have tested it and measured the sound with a sound meter and found that it works quite well. At about 85% noise reduction. This DOSE NOT restrict air flow, as this would not be good.

remixed_from.title: Extruder Exhaust Fan for Overlord Pro

description.text:
Inspired by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:942115 from chrisdug (many thanks!).

Printing ABS and PLA was never a problem for my printer. But printing flexible materials as Soft PLA from Orbitech was not possible if the print goes more than 45 minutes! The extruder then is around 40 °Celsius and the filament blocks in the worm-drive.

With this easy and powerful solution the problem is gone. The new extruder fan is turning on every time the hotend-fan (not the nozzle-fan) is running. I use the fan directly on printers body housing without destroying any structure. Works like a charm. See the instruction page for more details.

See the pictures in reverse order:

  1. print the mask if needed
  2. remove the stepper motor and put all cables away
  3. positioning the mask with respect of the plastic-structure (2mm vertical plastic wall as the black part begin!) and make the holes with a small drill bit (i.e. 2mm)
  4. increase all with an 4mm drill
  5. carefully do the final 8mm for all hole except the three for mounting and cabling
  6. remove plastic-cap carefully and extend the two 4mm holes for the screws to 8mm (so the nuts have space)
  7. mount the fan in the direction the hot air is blowing out of the case (my fan is from Conrad, 50x50x15mm, 24V, 1.3W for $7.- plus $1.- for the grid) with two 4mm screws and nuts
  8. cabling through the aluminium-elements (you can remove the plexi-rail available in each frame from the bottom, entering your cable additionally to the others and reinstall the plexi)
  9. connect to fan2 as seen in the picture (this is different to others who connect the additional fan to the second nozzle-fan, but I want the extruder cooler running also if I'm not using the nozzle-fan)

description.text: LLavero

Surprising that it has not been posted before. I found the stock K8200 extruder quite unhandy when it comes to changing filament and I'd like to try TPE flex filament.
I used http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:18379
and http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:498238 with a E3D v5 knock-off for 3mm filament.
When printing 3mm TPE do not overtighten the filament bearing! This leads to compression of the elastic filament and it doesn't fit into the hole anymore which leads to bending and jamming. The hobbed bolt grips flex filament quite well so you don't need too much tension.

The mount makes it easy to change extruders, since you only have 2 bolts holding them to the printer.

Print with reasonable infill (70% +). Mounts with 2x M4x20 (extruder) and two 30mm long threaded rods and nuts to the printer Z.

A few weeks ago I went out looking for a set of stackable bins. I was looking for bins for my work table, which is located in my small apartment's living room/office; so I wanted to find something that looks good.  After spending a many hours searching on google, amazon, container store, and ebay I decided to design my own set of bins. 
Stackables were created to store small electronic components such as resistors, capacitors, switches, leds, and pots. They are designed so that you can easily stack and re-arrange them. Each bin measures 3" x 3" x 6".  To date I have only created stackables using acrylic, though you should be able to use other materials have appropriate thickness, 1/8", and strength.

Here is what you need to get started:
(1) access to a laser cutter that is able to cut 1/8" acrylic sheets;
(2) two 12" x 12" pieces of acrylic, different color (enough to make two stackables);
(3) acrylic cement along with an applicator and the appropriate safety materials (rubber gloves). Here are the steps to create your stackables:
(1) cut the material using the supplied svg files (if you want to create two stackables, make sure to duplicate the laser cut lines on the project files);
(2) assemble each stackable in the following order: (i) attach side feet to bottom panel; (ii) attach bracket feet to bottom panel; (iii) attach back panel to bracket feet and bottom panel; (iv) attach side panels to side feet, bottom panel, and back panel; (v) attach the top bracket to back and side panels; (vi) attach the front panel to side and bottom panels, and side feet.

title: Simple Y-axis Tension Arm for Prusa Mendel

description.text:
This dead simple part is just a 50mm long bar with two M8 holes. One end carries a 608 bearing and the other fits onto the lower front rail next to the motor mount. Install as per the photo.   
You shouldn't need fender washers on the bearing (assuming your belts are properly straight) but don't forget the thin washers to allow the bearing to rotate freely.  
Once fitted, simply adjust to the correct angle to take up any slack in the belt (don't make it too tight or you'll be increasing the load on the Y motor) and then tighten the right-hand nut.  
Hopefully that should help to eliminate backlash on your Y axis

Very simple really. The only point of note is that I used a locking M8 nut on the bearing end and a short (around 36mm) M8 bolt that I had in my spares box. If you don't have a suitable bolt then a short length of M8 threaded rod will suffice - you'll just needan extra nut and washer. Two thin M8 washers to go either side of the bearing. Ensure that the bearing rotates freely before attaching the whole thing to the printer. At the other end, slide one M8 washer up to the right hand Y motor (lower) nut, then slide the printed part on, followed by another M8 washer and then the nut. Once fitted you will only need to use this last nut to adjust it. Complete parts list: 1x RP printed part
1x M8 threaded bolt at least 32mm long or thereabouts (you could use a scrap piece of M8 threaded rod - just add a second nut and washer)
4x M8 thin washers
1x M8 locking nut (or two standard nuts tightened together - stops the bearing coming loose)
1x M8 standard nut
1x 608 bearing
